In summarizing my own subjective thoughts about parasym plus, environmental triggers, and physiological triggers, I have some conclusions of my own: 
-Parasym plus helped a little bit to calm down my nervous system, as evidenced by being able to better access the parasympathetic system when close to threshold (but not over threshold). 
-Parasym plus improved my digestion
-Parasym plus somewhat improved my heart sensations
-Parasym plus decreased my conscious feelings of anxiety
-I do not think that parasym plus directly helped with my dizziness. However, dizziness and anxiety are always correlated (not sure about causation though), so if parasym plus calms the nervous system, then it dampens the catalystic affect of anxiety on dizziness
-Dizziness triggers include computer time, being at work, PMS/menstrual cycle, grocery stores, standing/sitting still, talking to people, and not being mentally engaged/distracted
-Work is a trigger because that's where I have experienced many somatic sensations (heart sensations, faint feelings) that have triggered fight/flight/freeze in the past. My uncounscious brain has coupled the environment at work with these traumatic sensations, as evidenced by experiencing fight/flight/freeze adrenaline surges at specific times of the day and with specific patients that I have had these sensations while treating. Additionally, the added anxiety of pressuring myself to do extremely well at work adds to this. Although I am not consciously anxious at work, it is an unconscious trigger that is attached to past experiences of traumatic sensations. 
-Grocery stores are also a trigger due to triggering somatic sensations in the past
-All symptoms (dizziness, palpitations, adrenaline surges, migraines, etc.) all seem to have some connection to hormones. Specifically, these get worse during PMS and my period. 
-I do not know what triggers severe, dysfunctional migraines. They happen about 1-2x per year randomly.
